<p class="notice--info"><strong>From Wikipedia — Universal Approximation Theorem</strong></p>

<p>The <strong>Universal Approximation Theorem</strong> is a foundational result in machine learning stating that a neural network can approximate any continuous function to arbitrary precision, given enough capacity.</p>

<p>In its most common form, the theorem applies to feedforward networks with a single hidden layer. With a suitable non-linear activation function, these networks can represent highly complex relationships by increasing their width.</p>

<p>Importantly, this is an existence result—it guarantees such a network <em>can</em> represent a function, but does not explain how to efficiently learn or train it in practice.</p>

